messages.text: I can‚Äôt tell you how nice it feels to have someone there for me.
I kind of have another confession.
Erin holds her breath, waiting for a response.
What do you mean, it wasn‚Äôt you?
I was in Vegas this past weekend.
Whoever you met accidentally wrote MY number on your arm.
What? Why did you pretend to be her?
At first, I was just curious about you. But then‚Ä¶
Seriously. I‚Äôm not at all sorry you liked me.
You don‚Äôt mind that I lied?
I mean, I‚Äôm not crazy about it.
But maybe we can try just moving forward?
And agree that we won‚Äôt lie to each other again?
And‚Ä¶can we also meet in person?
We can go somewhere public ‚Äî that way, if you hate the way I look‚Ä¶
LOL how about dinner at the Space Needle?
That‚Äôs pretty fancy for a first date.
Erin sucks in a deep breath.
How will I know it‚Äôs you?
Let‚Äôs do it the old-fashioned way.
I‚Äôll wear a white carnation in my lapel.
Wait, is that the old-fashioned way?
I think so. I saw it in a movie once.
It was a black and white movie.
So it has to be old fashioned, right?
Haha, okay. Should I wear a white carnation too?
Won‚Äôt hurt. We‚Äôll be a matched pair.
Don‚Äôt you want to chat some more?
Maybe‚Ä¶have a little bit of fun?
Sorry, but I‚Äôm not that kind of guy.
I don‚Äôt put out before a first date.
Right. But that was BEFORE we set a date. You know. For a date.
Haha, so now you go all ethical on me‚Ä¶
The next evening, Erin is quivering with nerves as she arrives at the Space Needle.
She scans the crowd waiting for the elevator to the top‚Ä¶
And spots a tall, handsome man with a white carnation in his lapel.
She approaches him, but a sleek, gorgeous woman gets there first.
He kisses her and Erin‚Äôs heart plummets.
But then deep, sexy voice surrounds her‚Ä¶
A delicious-looking man in an Italian suit stands in front of her.
There is no carnation in his lapel.
For the second time that night, Erin‚Äôs mood sinks.
He produces a bouquet of white carnations.
Isn‚Äôt that how the saying goes?
The mystery man pushes up his sleeve to reveal her phone number.
It‚Äôs written on his arm in black sharpie.
Erin thumbs at the other guy with the carnation.
I had no idea wearing carnations was such a popular thing.
She takes the proffered flowers and draws in their scent.
You are. Just as I imagined you.
You kind of look like her.
I mean, only a little bit.
Yup. Your hair is shorter, but yeah. Kind of.
Or maybe you remind me of someone else?
Are you sure we‚Äôve never met?
I would remember you, believe me.
Will laughs, and then lowers his voice to a whisper.
I‚Äôm so glad we‚Äôre here. Together.
Shall we go up and have dinner?
I‚Äôm too nervous to be hungry.
Me too, but the view is spectacular. You can let it distract you.
I‚Äôm excited to spend the evening with you.
And get to know you better.
Later that evening, Erin wads up her linen napkin and drops it on her empty plate.
And, as promised, the view is spectacular.
Will doesn‚Äôt take his gaze from her face.
It really is. I‚Äôm a lucky guy.
For a minute there I was afraid I might be sick.
Hey! The restaurant isn‚Äôt revolving that fast.
It is. I‚Äôm just ‚Äî you make me nervous.
I‚Äôm so happy to be out with you.
Erin places her hand on his.
My pleasure. It‚Äôs been great getting to know you better.
I never would have guessed that you were a kleptomaniac.
Will laughs, holding up his index finger.
That was only when I was six.
And do you still tackle girls and kiss them?
Kindergarten is such a tumultuous time in a young boy‚Äôs life.
And I‚Äôm happy to know you gave up your passion for litterboxes.
They are still fascinating and mysterious.
What with the buried treasures in them and all.
Will. Don‚Äôt look at me like that.
Yeah. Because I already have a boyfriend.
Yikes. Way to ruin the mood.
All right ‚Äî I‚Äôll admit it. I felt a mood too.
So why did you mention him?
Will takes her hand and rubs his thumb gently over her knuckles.
Okay. What would you like me to call you?
Mentioning him felt like an easy escape route.
That‚Äôs understandable, because I‚Äôm nervous too.
And I‚Äôll be honest. I really want to see you again.
But it doesn‚Äôt feel right, dating you when you have a boyfriend at home.
Technically, he and I don‚Äôt share a home.
But if you really felt that way, why did you ask me out in the first place?
You knew I was dating someone when you did.
I asked you out because had to know.
If this feeling between us was‚Ä¶real.
Before this moment, we‚Äôd only texted.
We hadn‚Äôt even talked over the phone.
And yet I needed to meet you ‚Äî in person.
I know I want to see you again.
But not while you‚Äôre still with him.
Erin sucks in a deep breath.
Are you saying you want me to break up with him?
I WOULD really like to see you again.
